did.abstract: The original goal of Artists Space was to support young, emerging artists, specifically those who had not yet had a solo show in New York City. Artists Space became one of the most influential alternative non-profit arts spaces in the Downtown New York scene, hosting a variety of prominent exhibitions including Adrian Piper's "It's Just Art" (1981), Nan Goldin's "Witnesses: Against Our Vanishing" (1989), Douglas Crimp's "Pictures" (1977), and Michael Asher's "Untitled" (1988). The bulk of the material is exhibition files, and includes research files, coordination, opening, reception, sales, touring, and dismantling. This collection also preserves artists' materials (CVs, catalogues, photographic elements), correspondence, drafts of published works, financial records, gallery floorplans and maps, grant applications, loan and legal documentation, and promotional matter in the form of brochures, postcard announcements, newsletters, posters, and press releases.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Materials in the Artists Space Archive document the workings of this late-twentieth-century art organization and all its attendant functions. Because exhibitions are at the core of Artists Space programming, the bulk of this material includes files that record exhibition research, coordination, opening, reception, sales, touring, and dismantling. This collection also preserves artists' materials (CVs, catalogues, photographic elements), correspondence, drafts of published works, financial records, gallery floorplans and maps, grant applications, loan and legal documentation, and promotional matter in the form of brochures, postcard announcements, newsletters, posters, and press releases. Documentation of Artists Space events and exhibition programming are also preserved in the form of images: slides and prints, drawings, paintings and collages, floppy disks, zip disks, cd-roms, and other digital media containing images, films, and audio. The research materials for the Artists Space 15th and 25th Anniversary publications also provide an instructive history of the organization.

acqinfo.p: The Artists Space Archive was donated to NYU's Fales Library and Special Collections in two batches, in 2010 and 2011.

bioghist.head: Historical Note
bioghist.p: Artists Space (originally called the Committee on Visual Arts, Inc.) was founded in 1972 by arts administrator Trudie Grace and critic Irving Sandler as a pilot project for the New York State Council on the Arts (NYSCA). The original goal of the Committee was to support young, emerging artists, specifically those who had not yet had a solo show in New York City. Quickly thereafter, Artists Space became financially independent of the State Council and over the years became one of the most influential alternative non-profit arts spaces in the Downtown New York Scene. Artists Space's original guidelines stipulated that well-known artists would select other artists to exhibit. Throughout the years, the gallery discarded this model, but retained the "Artists Select Artists" model for one show a year. Throughout the years, Artists Space, as a non-profit arts organization, has retained its commitment to exhibiting new and experimental artworks, and has expanded its scope to include readings, panel discussions, film programs, and special series, including the International Projects Program, Selections from the Artists File, and others. Artists Space moved from its original location at 155 Wooster Street to 105 Hudson Street in 1977, to 223 West Broadway in 1984, and to 38 Greene Street in 1993. In 2012, they opened a second location at 55 Walker Street. The Walker Street and Greene Street locations merged and they opened their current location (as of this writing) at 11 Cortlandt Alley in 2019.

Provocative programming has been the hallmark of Artists Space throughout its history, and a variety of prominent exhibitions are well-represented in the collection, including Adrian Piper's "It's Just Art" (1981), Nan Goldin's "Witnesses: Against Our Vanishing" (1989), Douglas Crimp's "Pictures" (1977), and Michael Asher's "Untitled" (1988). "Witnesses: Against Our Vanishing" sparked controversy, when, due to an objection to an essay by David Wojnarowicz in the catalogue, the National Endowment for the Arts pulled its funding in the wake of Newt Gingrich's moral crusade in Congress. The attendant controversy is well-documented in the collection. Artists Space has also given many artists their first chance at the spotlight, amongst them: Joan Jonas, Cindy Sherman, Jeff Koons, Sherrie Levine, Louise Lawler, Laurie Anderson, Barbara Bloom, John Miller, John Baldessari, Jack Smith, Andrea Fraser, Haim Steinbach, Tim Rollins, Lyle Ashton Harris, Ashley Bickerton, Peter Halley, Lari Pittman, Group Material, Stuart Sherman, Barbara Kruger, Laurie Simmons, Anthony McCall, Fred Wilson, Felix Gonzalez-Torres, Mike Kelly, Judith Barry, Michael Smith, Robert Longo, and Jenny Holzer.
For a full list of the exhibition history of the gallery, please see: https://wayback.archive-it.org/20123/*/https://artistsspace.org/archive

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: All efforts were made to preserve the original arrangement of the collection. The collection has been divided into eight series reflecting this arrangement. Within each series, items are arranged chronologically by event or exhibition opening date. The Book Files series is an exception, and is arranged alphabetically, then chronologically. The Media series is also an exception in which items are arranged alphabetically. The archivist transcribed folder titles exactly from original folder titles given by the organization. When they were changed, due to error or omission, they are denoted with brackets. The researcher should expect to find overlapping of materials throughout all series. Oversized archival materials from the various series are listed at the end of the finding aid. The first seven series are available for research while access copies of the media originals are not available. This collection is arranged into the following series:

Subseries A: Gallery Organization
Subseries B: Workshops

appraisal.head: Take Down Policy
appraisal.p: Archived websites are made accessible for purposes of education and research. NYU Libraries have given attribution to rights holders when possible; however, due to the nature of archival collections, we are not always able to identify this information.
If you hold the rights to materials in our archived websites that are unattributed, please let us know so that we may maintain accurate information about these materials.

If you are a rights holder and are concerned that you have found material on this website for which you have not granted permission (or is not covered by a copyright exception under US copyright laws), you may request the removal of the material from our site by submitting a notice, with the elements described below, to the special.collections@nyu.edu.

Please include the following in your notice: Identification of the material that you believe to be infringing and information sufficient to permit us to locate the material; your contact information, such as an address, telephone number, and email address; a statement that you are the owner, or authorized to act on behalf of the owner, of an exclusive right that is allegedly infringed and that you have a good-faith belief that use of the material in the manner complained of is not authorized by the copyright owner, its agent, or the law; a statement that the information in the notification is accurate and made under penalty of perjury; and your physical or electronic signature. Upon receiving a notice that includes the details listed above, we will remove the allegedly infringing material from public view while we assess the issues identified in your notice.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: This series consists of materials generated by the production of exhibitions and events at Artists Space from 1973-2009. Comprising the bulk of the collection, this material includes notes, correspondence, budgets, artists' CVs and slides, press releases, loan forms, exhibition inventories, architectural plans, travel itineraries, press packets, announcement cards, brochures, press clippings, and research materials related to the exhibitions at Artists Space. There is also extensive documentation of many of the exhibitions and events, through correspondence and exhibition images. Particular strengths include material related to the controversial Witnesses: Against our Vanishing exhibition, the national tour of Putt Modernism, the Artists Select series, the AIDS forum, and many more.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The original order of this series has been retained, which is chronological by the opening date of the exhibition, where known. For a full list of the exhibition history of the gallery, please see: http://artistsspace.org/archive

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: This series consists of a sampling of Artists Space newspapers, sent out as exhibition announcements, as well as a small number of production materials for these newspapers, documenting the process of their creation. In addition, there is a sampling of postcards and brochures, most of which come from the Film Series program, and span the years from 1986 to 1992. The brochures and postcards are duplicated in Series I: Exhibition Files.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: These files arrived without an arrangement scheme, and were arranged chronologically by the archivist by the opening date of each exhibition, if known. The files are alphabetical within each year.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: This series consists of materials generated by the day-to-day work of Artists Space. The material includes forms, templates, mailing lists, materials related to the administration of travel, materials for mailings, "workshops" files, correspondence, notes, forms, clippings, miscellany, meetings minutes, and staff retreat materials. This series contains two subseries, Gallery Organizationl and Workshops. Subseries B: Workshops contains materials generated by the production of a workshop series that Artists Space initiated in the first decade of the 2000s.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: These files retain their original order and are arranged chronologically by year, but the archivist arranged the files alphabetically within year. This series has been divided into two series, A: Gallery Organization and B: Workshops, which document a series of public workshops that Artists Space conducted in the early 2000s.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: These materials are arranged alphabetically, then chronologically. This series includes documentation generated by the research, fundraising, and production of the never-produced 15th anniversary book, intended to be published in 1988. In addition, this series preserves materials generated by the production of the 25th anniversary book published in 1998, 5000 Artists Return to Artists Space: 25 Years. This book is available at Fales. It is clear that the 25th anniversary book relied heavily on research materials originally generated by the production of the 15th anniversary book. The materials in this series include drafts, budgets, correspondence, notes, images, funding sources, brochures, catalogs, slides, interview typescripts, chronology, notes, and other research materials.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: This series consists of materials generated by the Independent Project Grant program administered by Artists Space. These grants were provided to artists to stage exhibitions, either solo or in groups. These were available to unrepresented New York artists to put on shows in non-commercial spaces in the New York area. The material consists of grant proposals, work samples, correspondence, and documentation of grant spending, budgeting and planning.

arrangement.p: This series is arranged chronologically, and alphabetically within each year.

scopecontent.p: This series includes the administrative files of both Lauri Firstenberg and Christian Rattemeyer relating to exhibitions that they curated. The material Includes slides, cvs, correspondence, and other files related to exhibition planning.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The archivist followed the chronological arrangement for this series, and arranged the files alphabetically within years for clarity. The files were removed from their original binders for preservation purposes, and the folder titles note this.

daodesc.p: Artists Space Archived Website: March 2014, November 2022-ongoing

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Artists Space (originally called the Committee on Visual Arts, Inc.) was founded in 1972 by arts administrator Trudie Grace and critic Irving Sandler as a pilot project for the New York State Council on the Arts (NYSCA). The original goal of the Committee was to support young, emerging artists, specifically those who had not yet had a solo show in New York City. Throughout the years, Artists Space, as a non-profit arts organization, has retained its commitment to exhibiting new and experimental artworks, and has expanded its scope to include readings, panel discussions, film programs, and special series, including the International Projects Program, Selections from the Artists File, and others. The website contains information and descriptions of current and past performances and exhibitions dating back to 1973; a list of all artists that have performed and/or exhibited at the organization; texts and images about events and exhibits; membership information; a calendar of events; and other general information about the venue. The Segue Reading Series is a collaboration between Artists Space and the Segue Foundation, an experimental reading series that has run continuously or 42 years. In April 2020, the reading series shifted to a virtual format due to the COVID-19 pandemic.

phystech.head: Physical Characteristics and Technical Requirements
phystech.p: Due to technical or privacy issues, archived websites may not be exact copies of the original website at the time of the web crawl. Certain file types will not be captured dependent on how they are embedded in the site. Other parts of websites that the crawler has difficulty capturing includes Javascript, streaming content, database-driven content, and highly interactive content. Full-Text searches of archived websites are available at https://archive-it.org/organizations/567.

accruals.head: Accruals
accruals.p: New site crawls are accrued semiannually.
